    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-02-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-02-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="1607"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1607">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.93/59.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Vice
                        Consul <persName type="to">Guyant</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 182.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 3, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your despatch No. 289
                    of December 29, 1913, transmitting a list of the Chinese firms in Ensenada
                    showing a close estimate of the present value of stocks of merchandise on hand
                    expressed in Mexican currency. You say that the general fear among local
                    merchants that the Governor will soon commence making forced loans of money on
                    supplies for the soldiers has led the Chinese merchants to make a formal request
                    for the protection of your Consulate.</p>
                <p>You are instructed to extend protection to the lives and property of Chinese in
                    your consular district in accordance with previous general instructions
                    regarding the extension of protection to foreigners.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilbur J. Carr</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
